WE MUST HAVE A SHUTTLE REPLACEMENT NOW<br>
 <br>
 <br>
     While all of us have been shocked by Columbia's fall from the stars, let us now turn our grief into resolve. Let us now call for a true shuttle replacement that can also serve as a Heavy Lift Launch<br>
Vehicle (HLLV), as was the case with Energia/Buran.<br>
 <br>
     Our future shuttle cannot be a tiny OSP (Orbital Space Plane) perched atop an EELV like the Delta IV or Atlas V, in that small spaceplanes will inflict great pitch-loads and bending moments upon such<br>
vehicles. To reduce pitch-loads, small X-20, X-37/X-40, HL-20/HL-42 mini-spaceplanes would have to be encapsulated within large shrouds of much more limber construction than the Soyuz escape<br>
armatures. Such a fairing would complicate escape options, and would further erode the already limited capability of such small spaceplanes. They are far too vulnerable to weight-creep, and their cost<br>
($9-13 billion--perhaps as much as $17 billion) will match, or even exceed, that of an Energia/Buran type shuttle-replacement.<br>
 <br>
     EELVs have no true 'engine-out' capability. Each Common Core Booster (CCB) has only one engine apiece. Should, say, a three-CCB Delta IV &quot;heavy&quot; (which uses RS-68 motors) have an engine<br>
failure in its center CCB--the first stage--its top mount OSP will have no chance to reach space. Should a strap-on CCB have its RS-68 engine fail--the results would be catastrophic, causing the launch<br>
vehicle stack to heave over violently before the range safety officer even has a chance to hit the 'destruct' key.<br>
 <br>
     However, were we to place three or so of these same, clean, hydrogen-burning RS-68 engines underneath one large shuttle External Tank (ET)--should one engine fail, the other two would take over and<br>
burn longer, since one tank serves all engines, which also happen to be spaced a bit closer together for stability, as was proposed with the MAGNUM booster and the related ALS/NLS systems.<br>
 <br>
     The Russians had just such an Engine-Equipped External Tank. It was called the Energia and was in fact its own rocket launcher. Unlike the Magnum, it had reduced pitch-loads and bending moments<br>
by side-mounting its substantial Buran orbiter. The Buran was very like Columbia, but had a safer design in that it had fewer connections to its (engine-equipped) External Tank. Therefore Buran had<br>
fewer &quot;holes&quot; or pass-thrus in its heat shield. (See www.k26.com/buran and www.spaceislandgroup.com as well as My Oct. 28, 2002 letter to SPACE NEWS, page 12.)<br>
 <br>
     Columbia's External Tank, however, had no such engines. This, sadly, forced Columbia herself to house its three complicated hydrogen-burning Space-Shuttle Main Engines (SSMEs) within the<br>
orbiter. This was done to re-use the SSMEs, which proved to be more costly than they were worth to return and refurbish. The SSMEs also developed cracks. That may not have been the only part of the<br>
orbiter(s) to do so. <br>
 <br>
     Let me explain.<br>
 <br>
     Once the Solid Rocket Boosters (SRBs)--that were fixed after Challenger's loss-- fell away during flight, the Columbia orbiter, which has the main engines, bore not only its own weight but that of the<br>
larger External Tank as well. Imagine walking backwards up a flight of stairs while bearing a grand piano in your arms. You do not need to be an engineer to understand that such a backbreaking load can<br>
induce heavy strain upon an airframe, causing metal fatigue which could very well have been the true cause of Columbia's break-up. <br>
 <br>
     I for one find suspicious the location of heat in the wheel-well near the wing-join to the fuselage. Should a weakness allow the wing to rise up a bit during re-entry, a crack, or rather a gap, in the tiles<br>
could appear, allowing access of superheated air to force the gap wider--first causing heat, then spalling off tiles at an increasing rate. The heat aggravates the initial weakness, leading to additional<br>
bending--and so on to the point of failure--even after maximum heating. It just so happened that the External Tank SoFi foam hit the same area, doing perhaps little, if any, real damage. By placing new<br>
RS-68 engines with new parts underneath a new External Tank that is then staged after only one use, the orbiter has a more benign flight environment that is more favorable to repeated use.<br>
 <br>
     Columbia's three SSMEs also had 90% more parts than the Delta IV's RS-68 engines, yet produce slightly less thrust. The SSMEs are so large that, due to their unfortunate location filling the entire aft<br>
fuselage, that they force the small secondary insertion/maneuver and de-orbit thrusters (the OMS pods) outside the orbiter's boat-tail. These OMS pods are the two 'bulges' to either side of the tail-fin. To<br>
save space, these OMS pods must contain pressure-fed hypergolic propellants that are not only highly dense, but highly toxic. These hypergolic propellants are so volatile that they combust spontaneously.<br>
Even so, the fuel tanks inside the OMS pods are only the size of beachballs, limiting the orbiters usefulness in space. <br>
 <br>
    These are what turned Columbia's remains into HAZMAT problems, although much of what was left cooked off and exploded--likely the two 'puffs' we saw in the debris contrail, with much of the<br>
remaining chemicals having burned away afterwards.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
     By relocating the large, clean, hydrogen burning SSME's (or their RS-68 equivalents) to the bottom of the External Tank, the orbiter is simplified, has a much less structurally demanding flight envelope,<br>
and can carry a tail full of safer kerosene/LOX propellants instead of a tail full of complicated SSMEs that are dead-weight-on-orbit after ET separation forcing the use of toxic OMS pods.<br>
 <br>
     The Russian Orbiter BURAN had the simple construction I call for. Buran could hold yet more propellant in the payload bay, with its thrusters in-line with respect to the orbiter. Columbia could not do<br>
this, since its OMS pods could not feed off of any additional propellant located elsewhere. The Buran could also be exchanged with very simple 100 ton cargo pods, being just another payload itself.<br>
Remember, the main hydrogen burning engines on this system are under the External Tank--which became known as the ENERGIA. The Energia pushed itself into space with the simple Buran orbiter<br>
along for the ride, where it placed itself into orbit with little effort. Energia could achieve orbit, (to be used for station modules perhaps) but is shut down to be expended to keep space junk numbers down.<br>
The Buran is what is known as a 'parasite' in that it bore no load, and could thus be swapped out with 100 ton pods. Four or five of such pods, and the International Space Station (ISS) would have been<br>
finished years ago. Since the 100 ton pods stay in space as structures, their launch can be achieved even if the weather isn't perfect the world over--a must for launching Columbia-style orbiters. Since it had<br>
the main engines, you had to fly 90 ton Columbia just to place a maximum of 20 tons or so in space. Columbia used to be even heavier, but it was lightened in order to allow it to visit ISS. Whether this<br>
played a role in its destruction is uncertain, but I tend to doubt it. With Energia/Buran, a 100 ton pod can be launched in one flight and a Buran-type orbiter sent to service it, add parts, etc. This limits the<br>
number of spacewalks and excessive flights.<br>
 <br>
     Energia/Buran is gone now, dying with the collapse of the Soviet Union, which was not destroyed over Buran's cost as some would lead you to believe. The failed Russian Moonship, the N-1, was even<br>
more costly, yet it did not destroy Russia in the 1970s-1980s, which was considered a time of plenty--for awhile. Their $20 billion Baikal-Amur Mainline, which still costs $200 million a year to operate<br>
helped speed Communism to its grave. The original Trans-Siberian Railway celebrated its complete electrification on Christmas 2002, after 74 years of work. So you have two Asia-wide &quot;Amtrakinskis&quot; as<br>
a costly burden, not to mention four generations of ICBMs, SDI, a failed war in Afghanistan, bad weather, etc. All this broke the USSR's back by the time Energia/Buran was killed.<br>
 <br>
     Yet Energia/Buran remains a good example of what our Shuttle Replacement must be--a modular workhorse. Its liquid-fueled strap-on boosters (Zenit first-stages each) proved safer than Solid Rocket<br>
Boosters. Zenit still serves the Boeing Sea Launch franchise, and the two nozzle RD-180 engine (derived from the Zenit RD-170) serves as the main engine of the ATLAS V EELV. Energia had<br>
tremendous engine-out capability due to its design. Buran, in its first and only flight, circled the Earth twice and was able to land in a 20 knot crosswind by complete automation--unmanned!<br>
 <br>
     Many inside and outside Russia try to downplay this accomplishment, but to no avail as far as I am concerned. Remember, its critics in NASA-Marshall who want the useless OSP minispaceplane are<br>
the same folks who gave us the X-33/ VentureStar flop--it being a cryogenic eggshell of a hypersonic blimp that had a poor shape, leaky aerospikes, and a weak composite hydrogen tank which burst long<br>
before it could even make it to the pad. Later, they worked on fanciful SLI designs that were no more realistic. The supporters of X-33 sounded like the supporters of the Sgt. York.<br>
 <br>
     We simply are not ready for SSTO/TSTO craft yet. Now these same people would try to sell America an EELV launched OSP that I and others have shown to be unwise. Will we follow them? Or will<br>
we demand something better--something we KNOW works, seeing that Energia launched with 100% success. <br>
 <br>
     Much has been said about the orange External Tank insulation (SoFi)--much of it false. This may, or may not, have been a factor in the loss of Columbia after all. Even if this proves to be the case, it<br>
should be no problem. In the very first flight of Columbia, the ET was coated in paint. This was omitted due to weight. It could be that for a simple lack of a coat of paint that seven astronauts paid the<br>
ultimate price--but somehow I don't think so. It has been said that the early paint actually pulled more foam off in places, causing smearing on the orbiter-- but newer paints and/or foam may help. Freon<br>
was said to have once been used in the foam, and was removed. The freon may need to be returned. Future side/top-mount craft will need newer materials in any event.<br>
 <br>
  Columbia's loss was most likely a freak. Some have suggested computer problems. Parts of the VAB ceiling have been detaching, in a slow analog of the Baikonur hanger collapse. Perhaps during the<br>
night, a piece got through the net of webbing designed to catch pieces of the roof. A night-watchman could have heard an impact, and thought the piece of debris had only hit the floor. Super-pressure air<br>
could race to the back, near a wheel well and move forward, 'filling' the wing. So a crack at the front could lead to the heating at the rear, moving forward. Ice vented from the orbiter should have the same<br>
relative velocity in space, so I do not believe it is the culprit. There has been talk about the failure of both wings.  Some of the orange insulation seemed to move toward the camera, losing focus. We will not<br>
know until more debris has been located, perhaps using methods employed by the Tornado Debris Project. It could be that Storm Chasers may even play a role, in that strong transport winds aloft may<br>
have scattered Columbia's debris in much the same way as a violent storm. Many checks have been found blown many miles away after perhaps being taken to the tops of the thunderheads.<br>
 <br>
     Columbia was the heaviest orbiter, had long been dormant, and was modified. Other orbiters have been &quot;exercised&quot; more often. Unlike the Energia/Buran launch vehicle stack, raised as a unit, the orbiter<br>
is 'manhandled' up to the side of the ET.This also may have caused something to pop. The airframes of all orbiters need to be double and treble-checked. Columbia was strong. But some bridges in<br>
seismically active regions are having reinforcements removed to allow for more room to flex under duress. If one removes the wrong piece however...<br>
 <br>
 <br>
     I ask for only three things:<br>
 <br>
 <br>
1.)      We must, in the meantime either improve the bonding/sealing<br>
           agents of the insulation and/or the tiles--or we go back to<br>
           painting the ETs with better paints. Payloads may be reduced<br>
           but we can get back to flying sooner. Freon waivers are a must. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
2.)      A two-fold increase in NASA's budget best done by killing<br>
           The Joint Strike Fighter (JSF) that UCAVs have already<br>
           made obsolete. The Crusader self-propelled howitzer program<br>
           and the Osprey--which has itself killed pilots, each cost <br>
           $10 billion, and are not needed.<br>
 <br>
3.)      Most importantly, we must begin construction of engine-<br>
           equipped External Tanks with simpler Buran style<br>
           orbiters, that will allow for landing jets, an F-111 type<br>
           Escape system, and, perhaps, a metal heat-shield--the<br>
           only good thing to come out of X-33.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
     Ron Dittemore, in a telephone conversation with me some time back, said that he had sent a memo requesting much the same things as in my third request (3.), since that would result in greater overall<br>
safety. He was not the only one in Johnson calling for such a design. He was ignored, however. We should ask why. Martin-Marietta had a similar concept for a Shuttle-C entry. The weight saved by<br>
removing hydrogen engines from the orbiter could translate into a heavier, more durable heat-shield in exchange. Flying in a &quot;heads-up&quot; attitude as suggested by some increases lift while decreasing the<br>
likelihood of further SoFi impacts upon the orbiter. <br>
 <br>
     As I said just above, there were others at Johnson who were talked out of Shuttle-upgrades. On page 229 of the work SPACE TRANSPORTATION PROPULSION TECHNOLOGY SYMPOSIUM<br>
(VOLUME 2--SYMPOSIUM PROCEEDINGS) which was held at Pennsylvania State University in June 1990--is the piece by Wayne L. Ordway entitled  &quot;SHUTTLE DERIVED MANNED<br>
TRANSPORTATION SYSTEMS.&quot; That author, before anyone got to him, called for an engine-equipped External Tank and a simpler &quot;Block-II&quot; orbiter very like Buran function-wise, since the design<br>
&quot;separates the launch function from the spacecraft, with an associated reduction in vehicle complexity.&quot; The author goes on to say that the &quot;available volume from removal of the propulsion system could<br>
house additional orbital maneuvering system propellant.&quot; This set-up would allow an orbiter to stay in space longer for possible rescue in case of emergency. This Block-II design would have an F-111<br>
type cockpit, as shown in Figure 4 on page 239 (Crew Escape Module.)<br>
 <br>
     Engine-equipped External Tanks (ETs) are nothing new. &quot;A core stage consisting of a modified ET with an integrated main propulsion system has been previously studied...&quot; Two citations are given:<br>
 <br>
(SHUTTLE DERIVED VEHICLES TECHNOLOGY REQUIREMENTS STUDY,  NAS8-34183, Martin Marietta Co., 1982)<br>
 <br>
(SHUTTLE DERIVED CARGO LAUNCH VEHICLE CONCEPT EVALUATION STUDY,  NAS8-34599, Boeing Co, 1982)<br>
 <br>
Please take note that these studies preceeded the launch of Energia/Buran, and were done before the development of cheaper, expendable RS-68 engines which make the powered-ET concept yet more<br>
feasible now than in the past. The (Boeing ?) Library in Marshall refused to make the studies available to me.<br>
 <br>
     I myself have also had a telephone conversation with the author of the above described work in an attempt to gain permission to copy his work, which I was told was unnecessary by others. The author<br>
said that objections over cost were raised, but this was before the even more costly, and unworkable VentureStar and SLI concepts of suspect design were proffered by critics of my ideas. All this before<br>
the RS-68 was flight proven, as was done recently.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
     If all of this sounds expensive, it is. But X-33/VentureStar and the OSP will cost just as much, if not more (in money, if not lives) to implement.<br>
 <br>
     We must not ask if we can afford to have a proven shuttle-replacement like what I have just called for. That is not the question.<br>
 <br>
The question is...<br>
 <br>
 <br>
Can we afford not too?<br>
 <br>
How I wish I could go back in time, so that America and Russia could swap STS programs. If Russia had made Columbia and Challenger, neither would have been lost in flight. One would wind up under<br>
a collapsed hanger, the other in Gorky Park. If America had built Energia/Buran, we may have kept fourteen people alive. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 347<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/19/03 3:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm28.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=50.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Article submission via email...</span><hr size=1> Um, I have an issue with the swap part.<br>
